Trails: This trail departs the Oxbow Bayou South Side and runs southwest to the asphalt trail off Highland Knolls. Nice pine forest near the south end of the trail. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 89’. Parking is available on the street on the west side of Pattison Elementary School, at the Walgreens at Highland Knolls and Fry Rd or at the south dead-end of Alana Springs Dr.

This trail starts on the east side of the Nottingham Country MUD treatment plant fence, then cuts cross county to the Mason Highland trail. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 92’. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 89’. west side of Pattison Elementary School.

This trail runs on both sides of the old Mason Creek stream bank levee. Near the south end there is an old Boy Scout bridge to cross from one side to the other. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 90’. Parking is available on the street on the west side of Pattison Elementary School.

This trail runs from the eastern most FFPS soccer field parking lot to the Old Rice Berm trail. This is cross country, so it can be muddy in wet weather. It intersects the tree line about 70 yards north of the Westheimer Pkwy ditch. Parking is available at the eastern most FFPS soccer fields parking lots.

This is a relatively short (350 yards/0.20 miles) connection between the FFPS Connector and Old Rice Berm trails. This is cross country, so it can be muddy in wet weather. Parking is available at the eastern most FFPS soccer fields parking lots.

A short (200 yard/0.11 miles) connection due east-west from the Old Rice Berm and FFPS Connector trails to the Westheimer Parkway ROW. Parking is available at the eastern most FFPS soccer fields parking lots.

This trail runs due north-south from the Mason Highland trail to the paved trail on the north side of T103 ditch. Follows an old roadbed on the north portion. The south portion runs on the top of a berm. There are two crossing ditches on the south portion which often have water. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 87’. Parking is available on the street on the west side of Pattison Elementary School, at the Walgreens at Highland Knolls and Fry Rd or at the south dead-end of Alana Springs Dr..

This runs on the south bank of T103 ditch from the north end of Old Rice Berm trail to the asphalt trail at the bridge over T103. Parking is available at the northern most FFPS soccer fields parking lots.

Roughly parallels west of Buffalo Bayou from Westheimer Pkwy to the south side of T103 ditch. There are three crossing ditches or low areas which often have water. One of them has a concrete pipe which is used as a stepping stone to cross the ditch. One of the lowest elevation trails, the lower (north) portion is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 85’. The higher (south) portion is rarely inundated. Parking is available at the eastern most FFPS soccer fields parking lots.

This trail runs from Westheimer Pkwy to Buffalo Bayou. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 89’. Parking is available at the Fort Bend County Freedom Park parking lots. Access is from Buffalo Bayou or the east side of the drainage ditch running south from Freedom Park. The trail crosses this drainage ditch and there is often some water in the ditch. Lots of gravel on parts of the trail.

This trail runs parallel to Buffalo Bayou and offers a lot more shade than the bayou bank trail. Usually done in conjunction with the Old Oil Field Road trail. Nice wetlands between this trail and Buffalo Bayou. Parking is available at the Fort Bend County Freedom Park parking lots. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 89’.

A neighborhood connector trail which runs from Cinco Ranch Equestrian Village neighborhood at the southeast corner of Fry Rd and Westheimer Pkwy to Freedom Park. Parking is available at the Fort Bend County Freedom Park parking lots or in the neighborhood near the Ranger Point Ct. cul-de-sac, Bronco Bluff Ct. cul-de-sac or from the ditch running south from Westheimer Pkwy just east of Fry Rd. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 95’.

Runs east-west through the old LH7 (Emil and Maud Marks) Ranch at the northwest corner of Barker Reservoir. Not much shade, so a great winter time trail. Access is 260 yards or 0.15 miles south of the gate on the George Bush Park (Barker Clodine) asphalt trail gate. Parking is available on Barker Clodine just north of the gate. A very pleasant low water crossing bridge is part of this trail. Trail is inundated when Barker Reservoir water level exceeds 88’. An “out and back” 0.84 miles one way.
Addicks Southeast to Woodcreek and East Fullerton St.

This trail runs from Bear Creek Park at War Memorial & Clay Rd. to Twin Lakes and Concord Bridge neighborhoods on the east side of Langham Creek & Horsepen Bayou. Runs all the way to Little York Dr. There are typically several low muddy spots which are east-west drainages flowing toward Langham Creek to the west. The signalized intersection at Clay Rd with pedestrian triggered buttons allows safe passage to and from Bear Creek Park. This trail will be inundated when the Addicks Reservoir water level is above 95’. Parking is available at the north end of Bear Creek Park near Clay Rd or, at Twin Lakes neighborhood via a greenbelt access easement at 13640 Sundowner Dr. or from Concord Bridge via an HOA parking lot at 5829 Bryant Pond Dr.
Bear Creek Park to Langham Creek to Woodcreek Trail
Bill Archer Bark Park to Cullen Trail
Brays to Keegan Bayou Connector Trail
Brittmoore to Eldgride via Drillsite Loop to War Memorial

This is a series of trails south of the lighted soccer fields and Alkek Velodrome. Several nice pine forest segments and two trails connect to a Harris County Flood Control District property to the south, with access to South Park View Dr at the south end of the HCFCD property. This trail will be inundated when the Addicks Reservoir water level is above 100’. Parking is available at the west end of the soccer field/velodrome parking lot, lighted baseball field parking lot or at 18200 South Park View Dr.

This is a series of trails south of the lighted soccer fields and Alkek Velodrome. Several nice pine forest segments and two trails connect to a Harris County Flood Control District property to the south, with access to South Park View Dr at the south end of the HCFCD property. This trail will be inundated when the Addicks Reservoir water level is above 100’. Parking is available at the west end of the soccer field/velodrome parking lot, lighted baseball field parking lot or at 18200 South Park View Dr.

Parking is available at the west end of the soccer field/velodrome parking lot, lighted baseball field parking lot or at 18200 South Park View Dr.

This trail will be inundated when the Addicks Reservoir water level is above 100’. This trail connects the Cullen Park asphalt hike and bike (which runs from Hwy 6 at Patterson Rd to Cullen Park off of Saums Rd & Park View Dr) to the Bill Archer Bark Park. Notice the massive oak trees just west of the bark park. The trail crosses Groeschke Rd, so be careful since this is an unprotected crossing. This trail will be inundated when the Addicks Reservoir water level is above 98’. Parking is available at the west end of the Bill Archer Bark Park parking lot (near the restrooms), on the north side of Groeschke Rd, about 1/3 mile west of Hwy 6, and at the Cullen Park trail parking lot on the east side of Hwy 6 just north of Patterson Rd. There is a small ditch, usually with water, to cross if you enter from the southwest corner of the Bill Archer Park restrooms.

This is an old roadbed, formerly known as Lamb Road. 0.83 miles due west from Eldridge to Langham Creek. Runs through some nice pine forest. You may see wood ducks in the winter time on Langham Creek. Also look for the old wooden bridge and concrete cattle guard over the north ditch. The concrete cattle guard is part of the Bear Creek to Langham Creek trail. Parking for one or two cars is available off of Eldridge Rd. 6/10ths of a mile south of Patterson Rd. This trail intersects the Bear Creek to Langham Creek and the Langham Creek to Woodcreek trails.

This trail runs from the Bear Creek Park southwest of Pavillion #8 on Sullins Way loop road through the old Boy Scout camping field, past the Hillendahl-Eggling Cemetery, crossing Patterson Rd, then passes an old farmstead and ends at the Eldridge to Langham Creek trail at the concrete cattle guard near Langham Creek. A very nice pine forest south of Patterson Rd. Parking is available near Pavillion #8 in Bear Creek Park or off the side of Patterson Rd.

This trail runs from the Eldridge to Langham Creek trail to a lake just north of the Addicks Dam and west of Eldridge Pkwy. The lower (south) portion of this trail will be inundated when the Addicks Reservoir water level is above 88’. Parking for one or two cars is available off of Eldridge Rd. 6/10ths of a mile south of Patterson Rd. or for multiple cars at a gravel parking area just north of the Addicks Dam and west of Eldridge Pkwy. There is steep ditch to cross just north of the lake, near the south end of the trail, which usually has some water.
